19 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
20 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
21 Article – Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis
22 12–102.
23 This title applies only in Baltimore City.
24 12–403.
25 (a) This section applies to a Class 7 micro–brewery license in the City.
26 (b) (1) The license may be issued only to the holder of:
27 [(1)] (I) a Class B beer, wine, and liquor (on–sale) license that is issued
28 for use on the premises of a restaurant located in the City; or
29 [(2)] (II) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, a Class
30 [D] B–D–7 alcoholic beverages license that is issued for use on the premises of the existing
31 Class [D] B–D–7 license located in the [40th] 46TH alcoholic beverages district of the City.

SENATE BILL 642 3
1 (2) THE BOARD MAY ISSUE A LICENSE UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(II) OF
2 THIS SUBSECTION IF THE HOLDER OF THE CLASS B–D–7 LICENSE RECEIVES A
3 LETTER OF SUPPORT FROM THE RIDGELY’S DELIGHT ASSOCIATION.
4 (c) (1) Subject to paragraphs (2), (3), and (4) of this subsection, the holder of a
5 Class 7 micro–brewery license may:
6 (i) brew in two locations using the same Class 7 micro–brewery
7 license; and
8 (ii) obtain a Class 2 rectifying license for the premises at the two
9 locations authorized under item (i) of this paragraph.
10 (2) The holder of a Class 7 micro–brewery license may brew in two locations
11 using the same Class 7 micro–brewery license if the license holder:
12 (i) requests permission by submitting a written application to the
13 Executive Director; and
14 (ii) obtains written approval from the Executive Director.
15 (3) Before authorizing a holder of a Class 7 micro–brewery license to brew
16 in two locations using the same Class 7 micro–brewery license, the Executive Director shall:
17 (i) make a determination that a second location to brew additional
18 capacity is necessary due to insufficient space at the existing Class 7 license location; and
19 (ii) consider any other factor relevant to approval of the application.
20 (4) Notwithstanding any other provision of this article, a holder of a Class
21 7 micro–brewery license may not serve or sell beer for on– or off–premises consumption at
22 the second brewing location authorized under this subsection.
23 12–1408.
24 (A) (1) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, THE BOARD SHALL ESTABLISH
25 A STANDARD TEMPLATE FOR MEMORANDA OF UNDERSTANDING BETWEEN
26 APPLICANTS FOR ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES LICENSES AND LOCAL NEIGHBORHOOD
27 ASSOCIATIONS IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS TITLE.
28 (2) INDIVIDUAL NEIGHBORHOOD ASSOCIATIONS MAY INCLUDE
29 ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON THE STANDARD TEMPLATE ESTABLISHED UNDER
30 PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
31 (B) IF AN APPLICANT FOR THE ISSUANCE OF A NEW, TRANSFERRED, OR
32 EXPANDED ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES LICENSE IS REQUIRED TO SUBMIT A

4 SENATE BILL 642
1 MEMORANDUM OF UNDERSTANDING, THE BOARD MAY NOT CONSIDER THE
2 APPLICATION TO BE COMPLETE UNLESS A COMPLETED MEMORANDUM OF
3 UNDERSTANDING IS INCLUDED WITH THE APPLICATION.
4 12–1604.
5 (a) This section applies only to the 46th alcoholic beverages district, which at all
6 times is coterminous with the 46th legislative district in the Legislative Districting Plan of
7 2022.
8 (K) THE BOARD MAY AUTHORIZE THE TRANSFER OF A CLASS B–D–7
9 LICENSE FROM THE 700 BLOCK OF WASHINGTON BOULEVARD IN THE 40TH
10 ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES DISTRICT FOR USE BY AN ESTABLISHMENT ON THE 200
11 BLOCK OF SOUTH HIGH STREET IN THE 46TH ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES DISTRICT.
12 12–1604.2.
13 (A) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO A HOLDER OF A CLASS D LICENSE FOR
14 USE IN THE 46TH ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES DISTRICT.
15 (B) (1) NOTWITHSTANDING § 12–2004(F) OF THIS TITLE, A HOLDER OF A
16 VALID CLASS D LICENSE MAY APPLY TO THE BOARD TO SELL ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES
17 MONDAY THROUGH SUNDAY IF THE LICENSE HOLDER:
18 (I) MAINTAINS AVERAGE DAILY RECEIPTS FROM THE SALE OF
19 FOOD THAT ARE AT LEAST 51% OF THE TOTAL DAILY RECEIPTS FROM THE
20 ESTABLISHMENT;
21 (II) EXECUTES A MEMORANDUM OF UNDERSTANDING WITH THE
22 RELEVANT LOCAL NEIGHBORHOOD ASSOCIATION AS DETERMINED BY THE BOARD;
23 (III) OPERATES AN ESTABLISHMENT WITH NOT MORE THAN 100
24 SEATS; AND
25 (IV) PAYS A ONE–TIME FEE OF $15,000, IN ADDITION TO ANNUAL
26 RENEWAL FEES ASSOCIATED WITH THE CLASS D LICENSE.
27 (2) (I) A CLASS D LICENSE THAT IS GRANTED A 7–DAY PRIVILEGE
28 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MAY NOT BE TRANSFERRED TO A NEW LOCATION.
29 (II) A NEW HOLDER OF A CLASS D LICENSE THAT IS GRANTED A
30 7–DAY PRIVILEGE UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MUST COMPLY WITH THE
31 REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SUBSECTION.

SENATE BILL 642 5
1 (C) THE BOARD SHALL USE THE ONE–TIME FEE PAID BY THE LICENSE
2 HOLDER UNDER SUBSECTION (B)(1)(IV) OF THIS SECTION FOR ENFORCEMENT OF
3 THE MEMORANDUM OF UNDERSTANDING REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (B)(1)(II)
4 OF THIS SECTION.
5 12–2802.
6 (G) THE BOARD SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS THAT ESTABLISH TIERED
7 PENALTIES FOR VIOLATIONS UNDER THIS TITLE, INCLUDING THE REVOCATION OF A
8 7–DAY SALES PRIVILEGE GRANTED UNDER § 12–1604.2 OF THIS TITLE IF THE
9 LICENSEE VIOLATES THE PROVISIONS OF THE REQUIRED MEMORANDUM OF
10 UNDERSTANDING THREE OR MORE TIMES WITHIN A 2–YEAR PERIOD.
11 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, notwithstanding §§ 6–308
12 and 6–311 of the Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis Article, a licensed establishment on
13 the south side of the unit block of West Pratt Street may keep and allow individuals to
14 consume on the licensed premises alcoholic beverages donated by a manufacturer or
15 wholesaler if:
16 (1) the alcoholic beverages are donated and served at an event for which a
17 nonprofit entity has rented the licensed premises;
18 (2) the licensee has provided to the Board of License Commissioners for
19 Baltimore City evidence of the nonprofit status of the entity renting the licensed premises;
20 (3) the licensee serves the alcohol donated for the event;
21 (4) any related taxes have been remitted; and
22 (5) the licensee only keeps and serves alcoholic beverages in conjunction
23 with a single rental contract.
24 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, notwithstanding:
25 (a) Notwithstanding § 12–1705 of the Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis Article,
26 a Class D beer and wine license issued for a premises in the 800 block of St. Paul Street shall
27 be considered unexpired until July 1, 2027, for the purpose of completing a transfer of
28 ownership at the same location.
29 (b) Notwithstanding § 12–2202 of the Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis Article,
30 a Class B beer, wine, and liquor license issued for a premises in the 6500 block of Eastern
31 Avenue shall be considered unexpired until the end of July 1, 2027, for the purpose of being
32 renewed to the current license year by the licensee.
33 (c) Notwithstanding § 12–2202 of the Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis Article,
34 a Class B–D–7 beer, wine, and liquor license issued for a premises in the 1600 block of

6 SENATE BILL 642
1 Eastern Avenue shall be considered unexpired until the end of July 1, 2027, for the purpose
2 of being renewed to the current license year and transferred to a new owner at a premises
3 in the 700 block of Aliceanna Street.
4 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
5 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 2 years and, at the end of
6 May 31, 2028, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the General
7 Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
